SIMPLE: halfway
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Halfway
<hw>Half"way`</hw> <pr>(h⟦aum⟧f"w⟦amac⟧`)</pr>, <pos>adv.</pos> <def>In
the middle; at half the distance; imperfectly; partially; <as>as, he
<ex>halfway</ex> yielded</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Temples proud to meet their gods <qex>halfway</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Young.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Halfway</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Halfway
<hw>Half"way`</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Equally distant from the
extremes; situated at an intermediate point; midway; <as>as, at the
<ex>halfway</ex> mark</as>.</def> <wns>[wns=1]</wns>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> center(prenominal), middle(prenominal),
midway.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>partial.</def> <wns>[wns=2]</wns>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>including only half or a portion; incomplete;
<as>as, <ex>halfway</ex> measures</as>.</def> <wns>[wns=3]</wns>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Halfway covenant</b></col>, <cd>a practice among the
Congregational churches of New England, between 1657 and 1662, of
permitting baptized persons of moral life and orthodox faith to enjoy
all the privileges of church membership, save the partaking of the
Lord's Supper. They were also allowed to present their children for
baptism.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>halfway house</ent>⟦br⟧
